==Wilhelmshaven Shipyards==

==Heligoland Minelaying==
While the Heligoland Bight lacks well-defined shipping channels, the considerable sea traffic from the Weser ports
 and the Elbe make it a worthwhile 'Gardening' site.

==Biscay Minelaying==
The Kriegsmarine launches U-boats from several Biscay ports.  As these are French towns, bombing them isn't an
 option, so they must be blocked off with mines instead.

==Fehmarn Minelaying==
The narrow straits of the Fehmarn Belt are a busy route from the Baltic Sea to the North Sea.  They also carry
 traffic from Kiel.

==Øresund Minelaying==
The most direct route from the Kattegat to the Baltic is the Øresund which passes Copenhagen.

==Kattegat Minelaying==
All shipping between the Baltic and North Seas passes through the Kattegat and Skagerrak, where reefs and shallows
 confine traffic to a few narrow passages.

==Baltic Minelaying==
These shipping lanes feed into the Danish straits as well as the ports of Kiel, Lübeck and Rostock.
